HTML 2.0	1995
HTML 3.2	1997
HTML 4.01	1999
XHTML 1.0	2000
HTML5	2012
XHTML5	2013

The <!DOCTYPE> Declaration
The <!DOCTYPE> declaration helps browsers to display a web page correctly.
It tells the browser which version of HTML the page is written in. The declaration is not case sensitive. All the following are acceptable for HTML5:
html

<!DOCTYPE html>
<!DOCTYPE HTML>
<!doctype html>
<!Doctype Html>

Common <!DOCTYPE> Declarations

    HTML5
    html

<!DOCTYPE html>

HTML 4.01
html

<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/loose.dtd">

XHTML 1.0
html

<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd">

Character Encoding for Chinese
To correctly display Chinese characters in most browsers and avoid garbled text, you must declare the character encoding (like UTF-8) within the <head> section of your document.

A Complete HTML Example
Here is a simple but complete example of an HTML page:
html

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Page Title</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>My First Heading</h1>
    <p>My first paragraph.</p>
</body>
</html>
